<Author>AsianPrince
<Content>5 nights stay-superb deal , very close but also very isolated, lousy breakfast I booked the room through Splendia.com for about $112/nts in Last April '08 and it was the cheapest without sacrificing the quality. But there are areas you can definitely will notice it cannot be compared to 5 star hotels.Initially, the night crew tried to check me into a very small cornered room, insisting that is the deluxe. Well, it wasn't and I insisted I couldn't stay there and the pics from my reservation were not the same. All of sudden, although it was fully booked in the hotel, one deluxe room was released and I could check into the better rooms that you can see in the pics other reviewers provided here. But it gave me a wrong idea. There was nothing you can do around that area at night-after 11pm. And, we walked around the little hutong around the Forbidden city wall. That was most memorable 2 hours of walk.Then we had a very late dinner across the hotel. This was a very small eatery where the humble locals hang out after finishing days hard works, The owner was a very handsome guy with great smiles to us, and he chose 4 dishes for two of us. And, it was most delicious meal I had for the entire 2 week stay in China. And, the food only cost us $13 with drinks. Unfortunately I did not know how to pronounce the name but it was next to the mart/convenient store across the hotel and it is open till 3-4am. Well, the location is great, at first, as you can walk easily to Tienanmen Square-20-30min., Yes, it is like walking in Moscow and things are really far stretched out but you could almost sea the east gate to the city wall. Very grand. But, at night, it is frustrating as the bicyclists approach you to trade something all along, or, even the bell boys cannot find taxi and we had to walk to the main street. The street itself is very dark but it is just like anywhere in beiing and I rather like it. There is no threat with the locals and you will feel safe anywhere.The bed was great, and the gas mask in the room was a bit funny. The shower glass booth is the excellent gesture with the curtain surrounds. The view to the outside is a wall and you would not want to peek out as it is a drab neighboring building just across a narrow alley.The breakfast room is still nicely located but I would not even compare it to that of Holiday or Ramada Inn in USA at $10. But, there is no other option around the hotel for the morning really. When we went to Silk Market and other new developmed area with CCTV, I found bigger hotels with Western Scale Boulavards but I thought the choice we made was still good and it was a definitely different experience as we actually stayed on/in the hutong, the old neighbors along the castle walls. That made the Kapok special. But, the taxi driver did not know the name even with the fully printed address in Chinese. So, that is the minus. If you like a good deal, you will be pleasantly surprised with the room decor and its size. And, If you like to hit two great walls locations in one day, hire a taxi driver for a day- $130 +$20 tip including a 1 hour drive over the olympic sites. it took us 12 hours and it was worth it for two.The hotel staff, Zhao Yao and Andy Liu speak decent English and their help outshined the minor incconveniences. They were really helpful., And, they wouldn''t take my tips initially on the check out day. But, in the street, the ordinary Beijing people are not that cool, but they are definitely peaceful and I find them more charming than Shanhai people. I hope they stay the same when i return someday. 
